# Bazel configuration for rusty-photon.
# See docs/plans/archive/bazel-migration.md for migration status and rationale.

# --- Core behavior ---------------------------------------------------------

# bzlmod is mandatory in Bazel 9 — all WORKSPACE support was removed from the
# binary (#26131) and --enable_bzlmod / --enable_workspace are now no-ops. We
# therefore set no flag: there is no MODULE-vs-WORKSPACE choice to make, and no
# WORKSPACE file exists in this repo. (Pre-9 these lines read
# `common --enable_bzlmod` / `common --noenable_workspace`; dropped on the 9 bump.)

# Enable platform-specific rc sections (for example `build:windows`) when
# present. This does not itself change stdout/stderr encoding.
common --enable_platform_specific_config

# Fail the build if a rule silently uses undeclared env vars; keeps builds
# reproducible and remote-cache-friendly.
build --incompatible_strict_action_env

# Emit full command lines when actions fail; tiny output otherwise.
build --verbose_failures

# Print test errors to the terminal instead of just logging them.
test --test_output=errors

# Don't bail on the first test failure -- report everything.
test --keep_going

# Tests tagged `requires-cargo` need a real Cargo invocation (they test
# cargo-integration code in bdd-infra). Tests tagged `conformu` drive the
# external ConformU tool against a service binary and self-skip unless
# CONFORMU_PATH is set. Both are excluded by default; run conformu with
# `bazel test --config=conformu`, or `--test_tag_filters=''` for everything.
#
# `bdd` suites run BY DEFAULT since 2026-07-06: Bazel caches test results, so
# after the first run only suites your change actually affects re-execute —
# and BDD failures (e.g. ui-htmx's snapshots of OTHER services' config.get
# output) must surface locally, not first on CI. The CI workflows are
# unaffected: bazel.yml's fast step and the coverage job pass their own
# explicit --test_tag_filters (BDD stays a separate CI step for failure
# attribution). Locally, the OmniSim-backed suites need OMNISIM_PATH or
# OMNISIM_DIR set (see the forwards just below).
test --test_tag_filters=-requires-cargo,-conformu

# Forward the OmniSim locators into local test sandboxes by name
# (bdd_infra::rp_harness::OmniSimHandle::start reads OMNISIM_PATH, then
# OMNISIM_DIR). CI forwards OMNISIM_PATH via `build:ci` below (kept there so
# the ci flag SET stays what it was); these default-scope forwards are what
# make the OmniSim BDD suites work in a plain local `bazel test //...`.
test --test_env=OMNISIM_PATH
test --test_env=OMNISIM_DIR

# Forward the Pebble locators the same way (doctor's @pebble ACME BDD
# scenarios — docs/skills/testing.md §5.6). Unlike OmniSim these are
# optional: the doctor suite skips the @pebble scenarios loudly when
# either is unset, so a dev box without Pebble stays green.
test --test_env=PEBBLE_PATH
test --test_env=PEBBLE_CHALLTESTSRV_PATH

# The `omnisim` resource pool. Every OmniSim-spawning BDD action (the four
# suites rp:bdd / calibrator-flats:bdd / session-runner:bdd /
# operation-watchdog-e2e:bdd, and each shard of a sharded suite) is tagged
# `resources:omnisim:1` and takes one token. Since #467 the bdd-infra harness
# gives every test process a PRIVATE OmniSim — spawned with the fork's
# --multi-instance flag (skips upstream's machine-global single-instance
# mutex) on a dynamically chosen port, with a per-instance
# OMNISIM_SETTINGS_DIR — so these actions can genuinely run in parallel on
# every OS and the pool is sized above the worst-case concurrent demand
# (8 rp:bdd shards + 8 session-runner:bdd shards + 2 suites = 18); it
# exists only as a throttle to grab if OmniSim concurrency
# ever turns flaky (e.g. `test:windows --local_resources=omnisim=1` would
# re-serialize one platform — --enable_platform_specific_config appends
# platform lines after this one, so they win). Profile-store isolation is
# the fork's OMNISIM_SETTINGS_DIR (release v0.5.0-467.2), which works on
# every platform — XDG_CONFIG_HOME did not: .NET ignores it on macOS, and
# the resulting shared store leaked session-runner's persisted telescope
# site into rp's shards on macOS CI. The pool MUST be defined or the tagged tests
# fail loudly with "Resource omnisim is not being tracked by the resource
# manager"; defining it on `test` (inherited by `coverage`) keeps it present
# for every test invocation, local and CI. --local_resources is a
# scheduling-only flag, so it does not enter action keys and never perturbs
# the remote cache.
test --local_resources=omnisim=24

# --- Rust toolchain --------------------------------------------------------

# Use the stable Rust toolchain channel for Bazel builds.
build --@rules_rust//rust/toolchain/channel=stable

# Drop debuginfo from Bazel-built artifacts. CI only needs pass/fail, not debug
# symbols, and debuginfo bloats the rlibs/test binaries the remote cache moves
# over the wire — keeping them small matters for a LAN cache and keeps CAS
# blobs under the Cloudflare Worker cache's 100 MB request-body (write) limit.
# Plural `extra_rustc_flags` (a list) so it composes with the per-OS
# `extra_rustc_flag` linker setting below rather than overriding it.
build --@rules_rust//rust/settings:extra_rustc_flags=-Cdebuginfo=0

# --- Platform-specific config -----------------------------------------------

# Override rules_rust's default gold linker on Linux. rustc 1.94+ warns
# about gold ("the gold linker is deprecated and has known bugs with Rust").
# The Bazel CI workflow installs lld explicitly. macOS and Windows use their
# own host linkers, so this flag is scoped to Linux only.
build:linux --@rules_rust//rust/settings:extra_rustc_flag=-Clink-arg=-fuse-ld=lld

# Forward GITHUB_WORKSPACE to build actions on macOS/Windows so qhy-camera's
# `libqhyccd-sys` build.rs can locate the QHYCCD SDK that the
# `ivonnyssen/qhyccd-sdk-install@v3` action extracts INTO the workspace there
# (`$GITHUB_WORKSPACE/sdk_mac_arm_*/usr/local/lib` on macOS,
# `$GITHUB_WORKSPACE/sdk_win64_*` on Windows). With `--incompatible_strict_action_env`
# the var is otherwise stripped from action envs. NOT needed on Linux — the SDK
# installs to `/usr/local/lib` (the build.rs's hard-coded, env-free search path),
# so the Linux cache is left untouched. On hosted runners GITHUB_WORKSPACE is a
# fixed per-OS path, so the action keys stay cache-stable across CI runs.
build:macos --action_env=GITHUB_WORKSPACE
build:windows --action_env=GITHUB_WORKSPACE

# Promote MSVC C4013 (implicit function declaration) to an error.
# aws-lc-sys's cc-crate feature check for __builtin_bswap* wrongly passes
# on MSVC: cl.exe in C89 mode treats the GCC built-ins as implicit
# function declarations (warning C4013, level 3) but the cc crate only
# sets /WX without raising the warning level above the default /W1, so
# the warning is never emitted and the check "succeeds".  This causes
# aws-lc to use __builtin_bswap* instead of MSVC's _byteswap_* intrinsics,
# producing LNK2019 unresolved-external errors at link time.
#
# We use AWS_LC_SYS_CFLAGS (not plain CFLAGS) because rules_rust
# overrides CFLAGS in the build-script environment with its own MSVC
# flags.  The crate-specific variant is read first by get_crate_cflags()
# and propagated to CFLAGS_<target> before the feature checks run.
build:windows --action_env=AWS_LC_SYS_CFLAGS=/we4013

# Disable CPU jitter entropy on Windows. aws-lc-sys's vendored C source
# compiles tree_drbg_jitter_entropy.c which includes jitterentropy.h via a
# deep relative path (../../../../third_party/…). Inside Bazel's runfiles
# tree the un-normalised intermediate path exceeds MSVC's 260-char MAX_PATH
# limit, causing cl.exe to fail with C1083. Disabling jitter entropy makes
# aws-lc fall back to BCryptGenRandom, which is the standard Windows
# entropy source and perfectly safe.
build:windows --action_env=AWS_LC_SYS_NO_JITTER_ENTROPY=1

# Bazel 8 enables runfiles by default on Linux and macOS but not on
# Windows. BDD cucumber tests rely on a real runfiles directory tree
# (bdd_main! chdirs to BDD_PACKAGE_DIR which is relative to the runfiles
# root). Enable runfiles so the source-tree layout is materialised.
# Requires long-path support (enabled in bazel.yml via the Windows
# registry key) and the short output base (C:/b) to stay within limits.
build:windows --enable_runfiles

# Windows links the QHYCCD SDK as a runtime DLL: `qhyccd-sdk-install` extracts
# qhyccd.dll to `$GITHUB_WORKSPACE\sdk_win64_<ver>\x64` and prepends that to the
# runner PATH. Bazel test actions run with a controlled environment that does NOT
# inherit the runner PATH, so qhy-camera's BDD/ConformU-spawned simulation binary
# — which still links qhyccd at load time even in the simulation backend — cannot
# find qhyccd.dll and exits before binding (every scenario then fails with "failed
# to parse bound port"). Forward PATH (by name) into Windows test actions so the
# loader finds the DLL. On `build:windows` (not the BDD step) so the --test_env SET
# is identical across every Windows CI Bazel invocation — a changing --test_env
# discards the analysis cache (see the OMNISIM_PATH note below). Linux/macOS link
# qhyccd statically (no runtime lib), so this is Windows-only.
build:windows --test_env=PATH

# zwo-camera's `libzwo-sys` build script (bindgen) + link step need native ZWO
# SDK toolchain env that `--incompatible_strict_action_env` (above) otherwise
# strips. The `install-zwo-sdk` composite action (run in bazel.yml /
# bazel-coverage.yml) exports these into the job env; forward them BY NAME so the
# value stays out of the analysis key (same pattern as the OMNISIM_PATH /
# CONFORMU_PATH test_envs below). Scoped per-OS so the Linux action cache is
# untouched — Linux finds libclang and the SDK (ldconfig'd /usr/local/lib) on
# default paths with no env. macOS needs LIBCLANG_PATH for bindgen (Homebrew llvm
# is off the default search path); Windows needs ZWO_SDK_LIB_DIR for the
# import-lib link search. (Windows test-runtime DLL discovery is validated on the
# first shadow CI run — see services/zwo-camera/BUILD.bazel.)
build:macos --action_env=LIBCLANG_PATH
build:windows --action_env=ZWO_SDK_LIB_DIR

# --- Disk cache ------------------------------------------------------------

# Keep a local disk cache so repeated `bazel build` across branches reuses
# work. Size is capped implicitly by free disk space; clean with
# `bazel clean --expunge` or by deleting the directory.
build --disk_cache=~/.cache/bazel-disk-cache

# --- CI-specific config ----------------------------------------------------

# Activate with `bazel build --config=ci --config=remote-cache` in GitHub
# Actions. On trusted events (push to main, nightly) a write token is passed
# via --remote_header="Authorization=Bearer <token>" (not checked in); PRs read
# anonymously and add --remote_upload_local_results=false. See
# .github/workflows/bazel.yml.

build:ci --color=yes
build:ci --show_timestamps
build:ci --announce_rc
build:ci --remote_download_outputs=toplevel  # build-without-the-bytes

# No disk cache on CI. Runners are ephemeral — nothing persists
# ~/.cache/bazel-disk-cache across jobs — and within a job one Bazel server
# (in-memory analysis cache + output-base action cache) already spans every
# step, so a disk cache contributes zero hits. It isn't free either: combined
# with the HTTP cache it routes every remote hit through the combined-cache
# write path, a suspect in the macOS bazel-build stall where every in-flight
# cache download freezes at once with no output (see
# tools/ci/bazel-build-watchdog.sh). The empty value disables the global
# --disk_cache above for every --config=ci invocation (bazel.yml,
# bazel-coverage.yml).
build:ci --disk_cache=

# DIAGNOSTIC (PR #474/#473): windows-latest's `bazel build //...` step
# deterministically fails a couple of ppba-driver rust_test binaries with
# rustc E0463 "can't find crate", varying WHICH target loses the race across
# reruns, even with the sandbox bypassed (build:windows --spawn_strategy=local
# above) and even with --noremote_accept_cached. The dumped .params files show
# correct --extern flags, so it isn't a deps/lockfile bug. Remaining
# hypothesis: with --remote_download_outputs=toplevel above, intermediate
# .rlib artifacts aren't downloaded upfront -- they're lazily fetched from the
# remote CAS only when a local action needs them as input. If that per-action
# JIT fetch is unreliable on Windows, a local compile action could start with
# an incompletely-materialized dependency, exactly matching what's observed.
# Force full downloads on Windows to test/rule this out.
build:windows --remote_download_outputs=all
# `--jobs` and `--local_resources=cpu=N` are separate knobs: `--jobs` caps how
# many actions may be outstanding at once, the CPU resource pool (left on
# auto-detect, i.e. the runner's real core count) caps how many can actively
# compile. `auto` ties both to the GitHub-hosted runners' small core count
# (4 vCPU), so network-bound remote-cache checks queue behind the same tiny
# ceiling as CPU-bound compilation, even though they don't need a core to be
# in flight. A fixed, higher --jobs decouples the two: local testing (holding
# CPU fixed at a real 4-core budget) measured elapsed-vs-critical-path
# overhead dropping from 52% at --jobs=4 to 15% at --jobs=50 on the same
# 2,500-action graph. 64 leaves headroom above that without over-dispatching.
build:ci --jobs=64
build:ci --experimental_ui_max_stdouterr_bytes=10485760
test:ci --test_output=errors
test:ci --test_summary=terse

# Tests draw from the same CPU pool as any local action (each test reserves
# cpu:1), so left alone at most HOST_CPUS suites execute at once. The BDD
# suites are sleep/IO-bound, not CPU-bound — each spawns a private OmniSim +
# its service binary and waits on HTTP — so strictly CPU-based scheduling
# under-uses the runner exactly when it matters most: a shared-crate change or
# dep bump invalidates every suite and the BDD step degenerates into a
# HOST_CPUS-wide tail (observed: 313-378s critical path on ubuntu, ~34 test
# executions with rp:bdd/session-runner:bdd 8-way sharded). But the opposite
# extreme — a fixed --local_test_jobs=8 against the 3-core macOS / 4-core
# Linux+Windows hosted runners — oversubscribed the box ~2x and traded the
# tail for timeout flakes in the suites that do burn CPU. Split the difference
# at cores+1: one suite's worth of overcommit keeps the runner busy through
# I/O waits without starving the CPU-bound suites. Bazel's resource
# expressions offer only `-` and `*` (no `+`) and Math.round the result, so
# *1.25 encodes cores+1 exactly across the 3-4-core runner fleet
# (3 -> 3.75 -> 4, 4 -> 5); revisit the factor if larger runners ever join.
# The 2x CPU pool stays as a non-binding backstop (6 on macOS, 8 elsewhere —
# always above the job cap) so declared cpu weights never bind below it. TEST
# invocations only: `bazel build` keeps the real-core pool for compilation.
# Like --spawn_strategy above, these are scheduling/execution-only knobs —
# they don't enter action keys or the analysis cache, so build-vs-test values
# may differ freely.
test:ci --local_test_jobs=HOST_CPUS*1.25
test:ci --local_resources=cpu=HOST_CPUS*2

# --remote_timeout is the per-RPC idle/inactivity timeout for remote-cache
# operations, NOT a total transfer cap — healthy byte-flowing transfers survive
# it; it only bites an RPC that has stalled with no bytes moving. Originally
# dropped from 600s to 3s as the confirmed fix for the intermittent
# `//services/rp:bdd` post-scenario park (PR #342 + the park experiment; see
# docs/plans/archive/bazel-migration.md): the park was a stale pooled keep-alive cache
# RPC that blackholed and blocked until the timeout, so a tight idle bound
# collapses it. Raised 3 -> 15 (2026-07-04): the spurious-retry risk the 3s
# setting accepted DID materialize — CI showed `Download of '/ac/…' timed out.
# Received 0 bytes` on PR reads and `Upload of '/cas/…' timed out. Sent 151
# bytes` during main-push bulk uploads (disproportionately the Windows leg;
# a 151-byte upload timing out is a slow first byte, not bandwidth). Failed
# main-push uploads leave holes in the cache that later PR runs miss on. 15s
# gives cold Worker+R2 round trips real headroom while still collapsing a
# recurred park in seconds, not the old 600 — and the park's other, independent
# fix (test:ci --spawn_strategy=local below) remains in place. On `build:ci`,
# so it applies to every CI invocation (build, fast test, BDD, coverage).
build:ci --remote_timeout=15

# Bypass the sandbox for tests under CI. Required on macOS/Windows (darwin-sandbox
# blocks the BDD-spawned ASCOM OmniSim from binding network ports) AND now on
# Linux: dropping the Linux processwrapper-sandbox is the confirmed fix for the
# `//services/rp:bdd` post-scenario park (the sandbox teardown, not the cache RPC,
# was the residual locus; mac/win already bypassed it and never parked — see the
# park experiment in docs/plans/archive/bazel-migration.md). On `test:ci` (inherited by
# `bazel coverage --config=ci`), so it also covers the fast-test step, which now
# runs unsandboxed too — acceptable, since these tests already run sandbox-free
# under Cargo. Scheduling/execution-only: does not enter action keys, so it never
# perturbs the remote cache.
test:ci --spawn_strategy=local

# Bypass the sandbox on Windows for the plain `bazel build` step too (not just
# `test:ci` above). Root-caused via PR #474/#473: windows-latest's `bazel build
# //...` step deterministically (but non-repeatably as to WHICH target) failed
# a couple of ppba-driver rust_test binaries (bdd, conformu_integration) with
# rustc E0463 "can't find crate" for several of their `--extern` deps — the
# dumped .params files showed the `--extern` flags were correct and complete,
# so this isn't a deps/lockfile bug; it's the referenced .rlib not being
# reliably present in the sandboxed input tree at execution time on Windows
# (sandboxed input materialization on Windows is symlink/copy-fallback based
# and known-fragile — see rules_rust's own acknowledged weak Windows support).
# `build:windows` (not `build:ci`) so it isn't gated to CI and stays scoped to
# the one platform that showed the failure; Linux/macOS keep the sandbox on
# `bazel build`.
build:windows --spawn_strategy=local

# DIAGNOSTIC (PR #474/#473), round 3: neither the sandbox bypass above nor
# forcing full remote downloads fixed the windows-latest E0463 failures --
# same signature, still varies which of ppba-driver's two largest rust_test
# targets (bdd, conformu_integration; by far the most --extern deps of any
# targets in the repo) loses the race. The failure tracks dependency COUNT,
# not any specific crate, which smells like a low-probability per-file race
# that just compounds across a large deps list rather than a deterministic
# bug against one crate. `build:ci --jobs=64` allows up to 64 actions
# in flight at once -- input staging/file writes for that many concurrent
# actions is plausibly enough contention to trigger Windows-specific
# file-visibility flakiness (antivirus scanning, NTFS metadata lag) even
# though actual CPU-bound compilation is separately capped by the
# auto-detected core count. Cut concurrency hard on Windows to test.
build:windows --jobs=8

# Forward OMNISIM_PATH (the install-omnisim action's pinned OmniSim binary path,
# consumed by bdd_infra::rp_harness::OmniSimHandle::start) into test sandboxes.
# Deliberately on build:ci — applied to EVERY ci invocation (build, fast test,
# BDD), not just the BDD step — so the --test_env flag never CHANGES between the
# Bazel invocations sharing one server. A changing --test_env discards the
# analysis cache and forces a full re-analysis of all targets (expensive, worst
# on Windows). Only the BDD step reads OMNISIM_PATH; the others carry the flag
# harmlessly. Forwarding by name (not --test_env=PATH) keeps the action key
# stable across push vs pull_request events.
build:ci --test_env=OMNISIM_PATH

# Forward the install-pebble action's pinned binary paths the same way and
# for the same reason (doctor's @pebble ACME BDD scenarios). Unset outside
# the workflows that install Pebble, which is harmless — the suite skips
# the scenarios loudly.
build:ci --test_env=PEBBLE_PATH
build:ci --test_env=PEBBLE_CHALLTESTSRV_PATH

# Forward CONFORMU_PATH the same way and for the same reason: on build:ci so the
# --test_env SET is identical across every CI invocation sharing one server
# (build, fast, BDD, and any `--config=conformu` run) — it never changes between
# steps, so it never discards the analysis cache. Forwarded by name; unset in
# build/fast/BDD (harmless) and set only by the conformu workflow.
build:ci --test_env=CONFORMU_PATH


# Remote cache is opt-in via a separate --config=remote-cache flag so local
# developers don't accidentally point at the shared cache. CI jobs combine:
# --config=ci --config=remote-cache.
#
# Backend: a Cloudflare Worker + R2 edge cache. Public-READ (every PR,
# including forks, gets a warm cache) and token-WRITE (only push-to-main and
# the nightly schedule hold the Bearer token — see bazel.yml). Worker code and
# deploy steps: tools/bazel-cache-worker/. For local builds, override this in a
# gitignored user.bazelrc to point at a LAN bazel-remote instead.
build:remote-cache --remote_cache=https://cache.rustyphoton.space

# Bazel's own fallback for an Action-Cache hit whose referenced CAS blob has
# been evicted from R2 is to invalidate that entry and retry the whole build,
# forcing a local rebuild from source for just the affected actions — no
# write access needed, since it's a rebuild, not a cache repair. But the
# retry count is a hard budget (default 5), and *without* --keep_going below,
# each retry aborts the whole build at the FIRST failing action and starts
# over — so one retry only ever fixes one action, and if scheduling reaches
# the same first failure again, it can cycle on that single node forever, no
# matter how high this budget goes (observed directly: 30 retries surfacing
# only 3 repeating digests, never progressing). This matters most for PR
# builds specifically: they never get the write token (see bazel.yml), so a
# PR can only heal itself by rebuilding locally within one invocation —
# there's no second, privileged pass coming to finish the job for it. Raised
# well above default so a build that's actually making progress (see
# --keep_going below) has enough budget to walk the whole critical path.
build:remote-cache --experimental_remote_cache_eviction_retries=30

# Paired with the retry budget above: without --keep_going, Bazel stops at
# the first failing action per attempt, so an eviction retry only ever
# discovers and fixes one broken action before the whole build restarts from
# scratch -- if scheduling keeps reaching the same first failure, it cycles
# on that one node no matter how many retries it gets. --keep_going lets one
# attempt surface and invalidate every currently-broken action instead of
# just the first, so each retry makes cumulative progress across the whole
# graph. windows-latest already carried this (bazel.yml, for an unrelated
# E0463 diagnostic) and was the only platform that converged instead of
# cycling; this extends the same behavior to every platform for the reason
# that actually matters here.
build:remote-cache --keep_going

# --- Conformu config -------------------------------------------------------

# Run the per-service ConformU suites under Bazel:
#   CONFORMU_PATH=/path/to/conformu bazel test --config=conformu //...
# This config just SELECTS the conformu-tagged tests. CONFORMU_PATH itself is
# forwarded on build:ci (above) so the CI --test_env set stays identical across
# steps; the --test_env here is only so a local `--config=conformu` run (without
# --config=ci) still passes it through. bdd_infra::run_conformu self-skips when
# CONFORMU_PATH is unset.
test:conformu --test_tag_filters=conformu
test:conformu --test_env=CONFORMU_PATH

# --- Browser BDD config (UI-testing plan Layer C) --------------------------

# Run the advisory @browser scenarios (real Firefox via WebDriver) under Bazel:
#   FIREFOX_BINARY=/path GECKODRIVER_BINARY=/path \
#     bazel test --config=browser //services/ui-htmx:bdd
# Firefox + geckodriver are external system tools, exactly like OmniSim/ConformU
# — there is no maintained hermetic-browser path for Rust (rules_webtesting was
# archived and never supported Rust). The @browser scenarios are themselves gated
# inside the suite by UI_BROWSER_TESTS=1 (set below), so the default `bdd` run is
# unaffected. This config is STANDALONE: unlike conformu it does not pigg-back on
# --config=ci, so it must set --spawn_strategy=local itself (the sandbox blocks
# the localhost WebDriver connection and hides the system browser) or it "works
# in CI, fails locally".
#
# STATUS (2026-06-23, plan §9 Tier 0 step 5 go/no-go): the Linux Bazel browser
# path is exercised GREEN — a local `bazel test --config=browser
# //services/ui-htmx:bdd` (system Firefox + geckodriver) runs all four @browser
# scenarios. They connect to a localhost WebDriver and a system Firefox — which
# the Bazel sandbox would block — so --spawn_strategy=local took effect as
# intended. (The run also emits a benign `cargo metadata failed ... will use
# manifest directory as fallback`: the insta golden-path resolver's expected
# Bazel fallback, all snapshot steps still pass.) macOS/Windows browser-under-Bazel
# is deliberately NOT pursued — but note this is the §6/§8 single-environment
# DESIGN, not the §3 escape hatch firing: that escape hatch (browser dropped off
# Bazel entirely) was AVOIDED, since Bazel-Linux is green. The @browser layer runs
# on one environment because P3 behavior is OS-invariant given P2 byte-equivalence
# (§2): the P1/P2 server-bytes layers carry the cross-OS guarantee on every OS, the
# orphan reaper is unix/Linux-only (§10), so a browser on every OS buys zero
# behavioral coverage. This config stays for local runs and the future ubuntu-only
# nightly @browser job (§8). The always-compiled `thirtyfour` dev-dep does NOT
# enter the required gate: the default 3-OS Bazel BDD (no UI_BROWSER_TESTS) stays
# green on ubuntu/macOS/Windows, verified by the shadow bazel.yml legs.
test:browser --test_tag_filters=bdd
test:browser --spawn_strategy=local
test:browser --test_env=UI_BROWSER_TESTS=1
# Forwarded by name (not =value) so the --test_env set is stable across
# invocations sharing one server — the OMNISIM_PATH/CONFORMU_PATH pattern.
build:browser --test_env=FIREFOX_BINARY
build:browser --test_env=GECKODRIVER_BINARY

# --- Coverage config -------------------------------------------------------

# Activate with: bazel coverage --config=coverage //...
# In CI also add --config=ci --config=remote-cache (see bazel-coverage.yml).
#
# Reproduces the Cargo coverage contract (.github/workflows/test.yml `coverage`)
# under Bazel:
#
#  * channel=nightly -- the #[cfg_attr(coverage_nightly, coverage(off))] on every
#    `#[cfg(test)] mod tests` block needs the nightly-only `coverage_attribute`
#    feature. cargo-llvm-cov gets this by running on a nightly toolchain; under
#    Bazel we select the pinned nightly registered in MODULE.bazel. Overrides
#    the default `--@rules_rust//rust/toolchain/channel=stable` above.
#  * --cfg=coverage_nightly -- cargo-llvm-cov sets this automatically on nightly;
#    rules_rust does not, so we set it explicitly. This is what activates the
#    coverage(off) attributes so test code stays out of the numbers. Passed as a
#    single value (not comma-joined) so it composes with the base -Cdebuginfo=0
#    regardless of how repeated list-flag occurrences resolve. Source-based
#    coverage uses the __llvm_covmap section, not DWARF, so debuginfo is
#    irrelevant to line/region coverage either way.
#  * rules_rust adds -Cinstrument-coverage itself for instrumented targets under
#    `bazel coverage`; we only choose WHICH targets via --instrumentation_filter.
#  * --instrumentation_filter -- first-party only; @cr// crates.io deps are never
#    instrumented (matches cargo llvm-cov, which reports workspace crates only).
#  * --combined_report=lcov -- single merged lcov at
#    $(bazel info output_path)/_coverage/_coverage_report.dat, split per package
#    by tools/coverage/split_lcov.py before the per-flag Codecov upload.
#
# --test_tag_filters=-requires-cargo OVERRIDES the base
# `test --test_tag_filters=-requires-cargo,-conformu`: coverage MUST include
# the BDD suite (like the default test filter, which has run bdd since PR
# #452), because it exercises the service-binary integration paths (main.rs,
# startup/shutdown, cross-service wiring) that unit tests never reach — and it
# additionally includes conformu (those self-skip without CONFORMU_PATH).
# requires-cargo stays excluded (those tests shell out to cargo). BDD needs
# OMNISIM_PATH (forwarded by build:ci --test_env; locally the default-scope
# OMNISIM_PATH/OMNISIM_DIR forwards above) for rp's scenarios, so a local
# `bazel coverage --config=coverage` needs OmniSim installed, exactly like a
# plain local `bazel test //...` run.
#
# Child-process coverage (three stages): under `bazel coverage //...` the spawned
# service binaries ARE instrumented (first-party targets matching the filter).
# (1) COLLECT: bdd-infra's spawn path sets a per-child
# LLVM_PROFILE_FILE=$COVERAGE_DIR/<pkg>-%8m.profraw when COVERAGE_DIR is set
# (child_coverage_profile_var in crates/bdd-infra/src/lib.rs; the `%8m`
# online-merge pool — not `%p-%m` — bounds the profraw volume, see PR #342), so
# each child's counters land in the merged profdata. (2) EXPORT: a pinned rules_rust patch
# (third_party/patches/collect_coverage_extra_objects.patch) adds each spawned binary as an
# `llvm-cov export -object` via the RUST_COVERAGE_EXTRA_OBJECTS env var set on the
# BDD/integration targets — without it the merged child counters have no covmap
# to bind to and are dropped. (3) MANIFEST: a second pinned patch
# (instrumented_files_include_data.patch) adds `data` to the rust rules' coverage
# dependency_attributes, so the spawned binary's sources (src/main.rs) join the test's
# instrumented_files manifest. Without it Bazel's post-collector LcovMerger intersects the
# exported report against that manifest and silently DROPS main.rs (it is reached only via
# `data`, not `deps`). Both patches are wired in MODULE.bazel single_version_override and
# guarded in parity.yml. See docs/plans/archive/bazel-migration.md.
coverage:coverage --@rules_rust//rust/toolchain/channel=nightly
coverage:coverage --@rules_rust//rust/settings:extra_rustc_flags=--cfg=coverage_nightly
coverage:coverage --instrumentation_filter=^//crates,^//services
coverage:coverage --combined_report=lcov
# Cap any single coverage test. An instrumented BDD suite (observed:
# //services/rp:bdd stalling under instrumentation while it spawns OmniSim) can
# hang indefinitely; the size=large (900s) timeout was observed NOT to fire
# under `bazel coverage`, so the action ran to the CI job's 60-min wall and
# uploaded nothing. An explicit --test_timeout kills the hang and marks it
# FAILED; with --keep_going (set above) the rest of the report still builds, and
# bazel-coverage.yml tolerates the resulting "tests failed" exit so the coverage
# of every target that DID pass still uploads. 900s preserves rp:bdd's intended
# budget (~400s warm) while bounding a hang at minutes, not the full hour.
# NB: the single-value form is a fleet-wide override — it caps EVERY coverage
# test at 900s, so a future coverage target needing more must switch this to the
# 4-value form (short,moderate,long,eternal). Both OmniSim BDD targets are 900s
# (size=large) today. If this still doesn't kill a hang under coverage (the
# size-derived timeout didn't), exclude the two OmniSim spawners instead — see
# docs/plans/archive/bazel-migration.md.
coverage:coverage --test_timeout=900
# conformu is excluded from coverage too: it drives the external ConformU tool
# (not instrumented) and only runs when CONFORMU_PATH is set.
coverage:coverage --test_tag_filters=-requires-cargo,-conformu
# Coverage keeps un-overcommitted test scheduling: instrumented BDD suites run
# much heavier than plain ones (rp:bdd ~400s warm against the 900s cap above,
# with a hang history under instrumentation), so the 2x CPU overcommit that
# test:ci applies to the PR gate is reset here. bazel-coverage.yml passes
# --config=ci before --config=coverage, so these later values win. Revisit
# once the PR gate has soak time at 8-wide.
coverage:coverage --local_test_jobs=auto
coverage:coverage --local_resources=cpu=HOST_CPUS

# --- Local overrides -------------------------------------------------------

# Developers may add personal overrides in user.bazelrc (gitignored).
try-import %workspace%/user.bazelrc
